No registration is necessary and the food will be distributed on a first come first served basis. Each family will receive 3 boxes of food containing mixed dairy, meat and produce totaling 75 lbs. Please drive up Bonadonna Avenue to enter the upper gym parking area and you will exit via School Street.

Join Miss Hendrickson as she reads “Please Don’t Make Me Fly!”. This is a growing- up story of self-confidence. Whether it's learning how to take the first steps, or how to ride a bike, children must believe in themselves and trust the adults who care for them before jumping into something new. Once Max believes he will be safe, our little bird spreads his wings. Click on the following link to enjoy this book with us: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hKr5yLRmf_58I-zPvvhe3dnS52pj_tRr/view?ts=5ee8063a

No registration is necessary and the food will be distributed on a first come first served basis. Each family will receive 3 boxes of food containing mixed dairy, meat and produce totaling 75 lbs.

Please drive up Bonadonna Avenue to enter the upper gym parking area and you will exit via School Street.

MMCSD is pleased to recognize our Senior Spring Student Athletes! We are recognizing different seniors who participate on the Varsity Outdoor Track, Varsity Baseball and Varsity Golf Teams. Today’s Senior Athlete Recognition for Varsity Golf goes out to Nathan Callaro, Jordan Davis and Conner Markel. Nate will be attending MCC in the fall for Computer Science. His favorite athletic memory is being part of the Golf Team and improving his game each year with the help of Coach Stout. Jordan plans to enter into the workforce following graduation. Jordan's favorite athletic memory is winning his first golf match vs. Keshequa at Woodlyn Hill golf course. Conner plans to attend MCC, majoring in business and minoring in Culinary Arts. Conner's favorite athletic memories are playing on the very successful Modified Basketball Team here at MMCS. Congratulations Seniors!
#MMPRIDE

Odyssey of the Mind World Finals 2020 is still happening— virtually! OM has encouraged students for more than 40 years to think beyond the box with creative problem solving, which develops skills in young people that help them thrive in our technical world. On Saturday, May 16th the Odyssey of the Mind Worlds had a virtual opening ceremony. Click on the following link to view the video of the event: https://www.odysseyofthemind.com/. MMCSD has one team lead by Amanda Lonsberry, participating in the Virtual Worlds Competition! Good luck Team!!

post_text:
Do you know someone who graduated from Mount Morris Central School District at least ten years ago who can serve as a role model for today's students? If yes, please submit a Distinguished Alumni Nomination Form no later than May 1st. Forms can be picked up in our visitor entrance or downloaded from our website using the following link: http://5il.co/2498.

Our 5th annual Distinguished Alumni Induction Ceremony will take place on the Friday of Homecoming weekend. This is a great opportunity to help our students understand the power of learning! When students hear the incredible achievements of people who walked the same stage they will be walking, it has a lasting impact and shows them that you can do big things when you come from a small town. The size of our school is one of our many advantages!

Click on the following link to view MMCSD’s Distinguished Alumni Inductees and their successes: http://www.mtmorriscsd.org/distinguished-alumni-inductees--3

#MMPRIDE

post_text:
Our National Honor Society (NHS) Induction Ceremony will be held this evening, beginning at 6:00 pm in the Auditorium. Students being inducted include Robert Hartigan (Senior), Mary Rose Cautivo (Junior), Sarah Robles (Junior), and Ian Lin (Sophomore). Selection and continued membership in the NHS are based on scholarship, service, leadership and character.

The scholarship standard is based on a student’s minimum cumulative weighted grade point average of 85.

The service standard is to complete thirty (30) hours of documented community service each school year of affiliation with the society.

The leadership standard is based on the student’s ability to positively influence others to do their best; taking challenging academic courses; going beyond what is expected; and participating in extracurricular activities.

The student of good character is cooperative; demonstrates high standards of honesty and reliability; shows courtesy, concern, and respect for others; and maintains a clean disciplinary record.

Crohn's & Colitis Foundation - Central & Western NY Chapters
January 31 at 8:00 PM ·

Meet our 2020 Rochester Take Steps Honored Hero: Vincent DiPasquale!

“My name is Vincent DiPasquale and I am an 8-year-old warrior with Crohn's Disease. I was diagnosed last year in May 2019, after months of living with horrible stomach pains, fevers, headaches, and years of not being able to really gain weight and grow to be a BIG boy!” To read more about my IBD journey, visit the link here: https://online.crohnscolitisfoundation.org/site/TR?pg=informational&fr_id=9109&type=fr_informational&sid=4062

To donate to Vinny's walk page or to start your very own team and walk with us on May 16th, check out our walk page here:https://online.crohnscolitisfoundation.org/site/TR/TakeSteps/General?fr_id=9109&pg=entry
#WhyITakeSteps #RochesterTakeStep

Join us tomorrow, Saturday, February 1st for our Senior Recognition Night and our 11th annual Coaches vs. Cancer Event! It’s a full day of basketball, Mount Morris versus York. The on-court action will open with Girls JV at 1:00, followed by Boys JV at 2:30, Girls Varsity at 4:00, and closes with the Boys Varsity game as well as the Senior Recognition Night for Boys and Girls Basketball and Indoor Track and Field at 5:30.

At half-time of the Boys Varsity Game we will be honoring our loved ones who have been affected by cancer with a very special slideshow. You won’t want to miss it! We will be asking for a $2.00 donation upon entry to the event. 100% of the proceeds from the event sales will go to local families battling cancer and the regional American Cancer Society.
#MMPRIDE

post_text:
Through the K-12 Sequential Dramatics Program, produced by Merry-Go-Round Youth Theatre, MMCSD is one of more than 180 schools in New York State to bring live professional theatre to our students. As the largest touring children’s theatre in Upstate New York and one of the largest in the country, the Merry-Go-Round Youth Theatre provides a complete series of curriculum-based plays, classroom lessons, and creative workshops throughout the school year to provide a continuum of learning across the grade levels.

Today, we were excited to welcome back a very talented group of performers! The performers led individual classroom discussions for our PreK and Kindergarten students. Afterwards they presented a play called “Do You See What I See in the Sea?”. The play was about an underwater adventure, a treasure hunt, helping others, making new friendships, and sharing.
#MMPRIDE

Join us on Saturday, February 1st for our 11th annual Coaches vs. Cancer Event! This event is a full day of basketball, Mount Morris versus York. Both communities put forth a great deal of heartfelt energy and time into organizing this charitable fundraising event. The on-court action opens with Girls JV at 1:00, followed by Boys JV at 2:30, Girls Varsity at 4:00, and closes with the Boys Varsity game at 5:30. During half-time we will be honoring our loved ones who have been affected by cancer with a slideshow. If you would like to submit a friend or family-member, please email Marcie Prinzi at marcieprinzi@gmail.com by Monday, January 27th with a photo, the name of the individual, the type of cancer, and "in memory of" or "in honor of". A $5.00 donation is requested for each submission, which can be given at the event. Click on the following link for additional information and to read the full article: http://www.mtmorriscsd.org/article/173009.
#MMPRIDE #CoachesVsCancer

post_text: Mount Morris Dam and Recreation Area is very excited to host another successful Winter Discovery Series! This year's theme is "Land of the Free". Starting Saturday, February 15th at 1pm, subject experts will be discussing topics relating to this region including Livingston County's Bicentennial, Genesee Valley historic figures, National Parks and exploring the world. Don't miss this opportunity to learn more about the dynamic Genesee River Valley! All lectures take place on Saturdays at 1pm (February 15th - April 11th). Lectures are free and open to the public at the Mount Morris Dam Visitor Center: 6103 Visitor Center Rd in Mount Morris, NY 14510 (off of 408 between Mount Morris and Nunda). If you have any questions about the Winter Discovery Series, please contact the Mount Morris Dam Visitor Center at (585)658-4790. Click on the following link to view the flyer: https://5il.co/ca3r.

Congratulations to our Varsity Boys Indoor Track and Field Team! During Friday’s meet at RIT, two new school records were set. Peyton Martin set a new school record in Shot Put by throwing an impressive 37' 8.5", ranking him in 3rd place in Class D for sectionals. The boys 4X200 relay team: Jesse Bacon, Ryan Morgan, Brandon Flint, and Robbie Hartigan set a new school record with a run time of 1:43.8, which places them in 3rd place in all of Class D. Go Blue Devils!! Our next meet is on Friday, January 17th at 5:30 pm at Houghton College. Click on the following link to view our full athletic calendar: https://5il.co/adam

post_text:
The Elementary Spelling Bee competition is this Thursday, January 9th. This is an all-day event beginning at 8:50 am in our Auditorium. The sixth grade champion will compete in the Regional Spelling Bee which will take place at Genesee Community College in March! Beginning on Wednesday, our Basketball and Indoor Track & Field teams have full schedules through Saturday! Click on the following link to view the athletic calendar: https://www.sectionvny.org/public/genie/783/school/4815/date/2020-01-08/view/week/.
#MMPRIDE #BLUEDEVILS

post_text:
At our PRIDE Assembly, the following students received the Mount Morris Elementary School PRIDE Award for being Trustworthy: Victoria Antomarrchi Rivera, Addyson Barnhardt, Cameron Constantino, Tyler Gilbride, Mason Grover, Saydi Henry, Liam Lafferty, Allison LaGeorge, Brayden Lewis, Rylee Lippens, Angely Lopez Limardo, Evan Mann, Kaylee Marino, Casey McLaughlin, Ryan Painter, Jolene Rawleigh, Ceci Rivera, William Sanderson, Graciana Soto, Penelopi Thiele, Aleigha Williams. If you see any of these students please congratulate them!! Next month our PRIDE word is Responsible. Talk to your child about the importance of doing what is expected of you. We are always so proud of all our students!
#MMPRIDE
